{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17531484","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17531484"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:15:27+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:15:27+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14601"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14601","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14601"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.81,0.12,0.04,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7294"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57328"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7294","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7294"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14601"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42787"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"3735"},{"type":"tags","id":"3736"},{"type":"tags","id":"4965"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"17838"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44315"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57328","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/57328"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 58-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-month history of headaches, facial flushing, and itching after hot showers. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, she appears plethoric. Her pulse rate is 88/min, blood pressure 150/95 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. Her spleen is palpable 2 cm below the costal margin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBlood tests reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EHaemoglobin: 185 g/L (115-160)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EWhite cell count: 13.5 x 10^9/L (4.0-11.0)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EPlatelet count: 650 x 10^9/L (150-400)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EHaematocrit: 0.56 (0.36-0.46)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EErythropoietin: 3 mU/mL (4-27)\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following gene mutations is most likely to be present?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["CALR","JAK2 V617F","BCR::ABL1","MPL W515L","KIT D816V"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic features of polycythaemia vera (PV), including headaches, pruritus after warm showers (aquagenic pruritus), and plethora. The blood tests show elevation in all three cell lines (panmyelosis) with a suppressed erythropoietin level, which is characteristic of PV.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EJAK2 V617F\u003C/strong\u003E mutation is present in over 95% of cases of PV. This acquired mutation leads to constitutive activation of the JAK2 tyrosine kinase, resulting in increased production of red cells, white cells, and platelets independent of normal regulatory mechanisms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003EBCR::ABL1\u003C/strong\u003E fusion gene is the hallmark of chronic myeloid leukaemia (CML). While CML can present with elevated counts in all cell lines, it typically shows marked leucocytosis with a characteristic left shift in the white cell differential, which is not seen here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECALR\u003C/strong\u003E mutations are found in approximately 25% of patients with essential thrombocythaemia or primary myelofibrosis but are not associated with PV. These patients typically present with isolated thrombocytosis rather than elevation in all cell lines.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMPL W515L\u003C/strong\u003E mutations are found in a small percentage of patients with essential thrombocythaemia or primary myelofibrosis. Like CALR mutations, they are not associated with PV.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EKIT D816V\u003C/strong\u003E mutation is characteristic of systemic mastocytosis, a different myeloproliferative disorder characterised by abnormal mast cell infiltration of various tissues. It does not typically cause the blood count abnormalities seen in this case.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The JAK2 V617F mutation is present in over 95% of patients with polycythaemia vera.","Polycythaemia vera is characterised by increased red cell mass, often with concurrent elevation in white cells and platelets.","Symptoms of polycythaemia vera include headache, visual disturbance, and pruritus after warm showers."],"references":["Tefferi A, Barbui T. Polycythemia vera: 2024 update on diagnosis, risk-stratification, and management. Am J Hematol. 2023;98(9):1465-1487. doi:10.1002/ajh.27002"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42787"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14601"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42787","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/42787"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-26T06:53:53+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-26T06:55:49+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7294"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57328"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"13","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/13"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\ude78","name":"Haematology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"3735","links":{"self":"https://app.